<HEADLINE>
<P>
RITA DOVE REMEMBERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"A poem should not mean but be." Rita Dove's intriguing "Genetic Expedition" 
(Book Review, Sept. 17) is, but it would have become even more meaningful to 
many readers if you had provided more information about her than just her 
photo. For example, the lines "My child has / her father's hips, his hair / 
like the miller's daughter, combed gold" could be appreciated even more by 
knowing that her German-born husband sports a blond mane. (He is Fred Viehbahn, 
prize-winning novelist and essayist, as well as a guest professor at American 
universities.) 
</P>
<P>
The mention of German bread and radishes for breakfast, as well as the shades 
of Rumpelstiltskin, do echo her immersion in German culture with a 
Fulbright/Hays Fellowship in 1974-75. I know, because I arranged for her visit 
in November 1981 to Cal State University, Fullerton. She lectured in perfect 
German in my advanced literature class and in delightful English to a class on 
American poetry. 
</P>
<P>
G. BORDING MATHIEU 
</P>
<P>
LAGUNA BEACH 
</P>
<P>
Founding Chair and Professor Emeritus of 
</P>
<P>
German, Dept. of Foreign Languages &amp; 
</P>
<P>
Literatures, Cal State Fullerton 
</P>
