<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: DATELINE SOWETO TRAVELS WITH BLACK SOUTH AFRICAN REPORTERS 
BY WILLIAM FINNEGAN (HARPER &amp; ROW: $8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1986, William Finnegan visited South Africa to profile the black journalists 
working there. His terse account of his travels through the black ghettos and 
sham homelands conveys the reality of life in that strife-ridden country with 
an immediacy that "A Dry White Season" lacks. 
</P>
<P>
The most interesting chapters in "Dateline" focus on the paradox of liberal 
South African papers that hire black writers and support the idea of a more 
equitable society, but have no black editors. Finnegan's descriptions of the 
struggle to report the news despite governmental decrees (like Humpty-Dumpty, 
the security forces assert that "subversive" means whatever they choose) and 
the murderous factional struggles within the black community fostered by the 
government, stand as a powerful indictment of the South African regime. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
