workshop is filled with colorful marbles and glowing glass beads. ; Photo, 
COLOR, She weaves them into one-of-a-kind silver wire bracelets, such as the 
one shown at right. ; Photo, A third-generation jeweler, Yves Kamioner, right, 
left his family's shop in Belgium to open his own studio in West Hollywood, 
where he creates custom pieces for a diverse clientele. ; Photo, COLOR, His 
$34,000 treasure chest, above, was commissioned by a collector. ; Photo, 
Melissa Tucker, left, a native of Sydney, Australia, uses her one-of-a-kind 
gold and silver jewelry to express concerns about the environment. Birds and 
fish are recurring themes in Tucker's work. ; Photo, COLOR, Her necklace, 
below, has a distinctive primitive quality. ; Photo, Valerie Mitchell, above, 
makes lightweight brooches and hair ornaments resembling bridge abutments and 
other architectural forms, such as the ones shown at right. ; Photo, COLOR, Her 
signature look is sophisticated metal jewelry with unusual finishes. ; Photo, 
San Diego-based designer Debra Stoner, above, is an artist-in-residence at the 
