<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNFAIR TO COMMUNISTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jules Feiffer's depiction of the aging communist of the '30s (Sept. 24) 
couldn't be more unfair. Most people who joined the Communist Party ended their 
membership when they were able to divine the villainy of Stalin. Some stayed 
with the resolve to improve their party. I am aware of none who have concealed 
from their consciences the many ugly realities of the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
To those types of Depression-era communists, the right-headedness of Gorbachev 
is certainly no embarrassment. Given their disillusionment, their dedication to 
progress and the persecution they have suffered in this country, it should be 
of surprise to no one that they may look upon his actions with a certain amount 
of suspicion. 
</P>
<P>
Then again, Jules Feiffer is a rather admirable fellow himself, not to mention 
creative and intelligent. It's entirely possible that the grumpy old man in his 
cartoon is not the run-of-the-mine American Red at all, but rather the breed 
apart: that sanctimonious coward who will call himself by whatever name is 
fashionable at the time. 
</P>
<P>
RONALD WEBSTER 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
