<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRITISH GET MOST OF THE THEATER MONEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding Dan Sullivan's article ("A Birthday Wish for Music Center," Sept. 17) 
calling for a classical theater company to be finally formed at the Music 
Center, sure why not? But to then advocate a director with strong classical 
credentials "which therefore may suggest a Brit," only undermines his exciting 
proposal and shows a total misunderstanding of where the American theater is 
today. 
</P>
<P>
Sadly our biggest problem in the area of classical theater still seems to be an 
incredible inferiority complex. Even our own theater producers and professional 
practitioners (not to even mention critics) find it hard to believe what 
training, exposure to foreign works and just sheer hard work has accomplished 
in the last 25 years in this country. Instead, we just keep on handing the ball 
over to the Brits every time we can, assuming no American directors have the 
proper cultural "genes" to be first-rate with the classics. 
</P>
<P>
In our own back yard alone, Jack O'Brian of the Old Globe, Des McAnuff of La 
Jolla, Dan Sullivan (our critic's namesake in Seattle) and Adrian Hall have 
gained world-class distinction as classical directors, and its time they were 
recognized as such by our own L.A. critic. 
</P>
<P>
Since time and time again American money has gone to support the Royal 
Shakespeare Co. and the BBC Shakespeare series, no wonder we can't raise enough 
interest and money to produce our own classical projects like the one Sullivan 
proposes. 
</P>
<P>
ROGER HENDRICKS SIMON 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
