<HEADLINE>
<P>
PASTIMES: AROUND HOME; 
</P>
<P>
BUILDING DOLL HOUSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUDITH SIMS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MINIATURES ARE fascinating -- we stare in rapture at teeny sofas, tiny beds and 
itty-bitsy plates when we wouldn't even notice their life-size counterparts. 
We're completely enchanted by a 4-inch pipe organ that really plays or 1-inch 
boots that lace up. We marvel at little staircases and wee ovens. 
</P>
<P>
Miniatures are a huge business these days, and almost every miniature is 
related to a doll house. Victorian or modern, cottage or mansion, bakery or 
stable, doll houses are still special gifts for little girls, but they are also 
compelling hobbies for adults. 
</P>
<P>
Although some people buy everything for the well-furnished doll house, most 
feel that they have to make something -- maybe the house itself, or the 
curtains. One doll-house book author made ceramic dishes and shaped and welded 
a set of copper pots for the kitchen. But nothing equals the amazing doll house 
owned by former silent-film star Colleen Moore that is on display at Chicago's 
Museum of Science and Industry. Moore commissioned Hollywood set designers and 
miniaturists to craft the fairy-tale castle and its furniture; two chairs were 
made using Moore's diamond-and-emerald jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
Perfectly fine doll houses can be made from shoe boxes and orange crates, 
although most of us might prefer a three-story brownstone or antebellum 
plantation. Once the shell is made or bought, the fun begins: decorating. Doll 
house aficionados today can choose from hundreds of items, in stores and 
mail-order catalogues: hardwood floors, Art Nouveau wallpaper, itty-bitty 
bathtubs and mini-magazines. 
</P>
<P>
 Classes in miniature construction are available at Lilliput's in Torrance, 
which also has all sorts of supplies (such as lighting, tiny books, gardening 
tools, landscaping items, brickwork and holiday decor). Angela's Miniature 
World in Camarillo offers classes for various projects (such as complete house 
building, making miniature food and doing electrical wiring) and also has a 
full line of supplies and kits. Accent on Miniatures in Laguna Hills has no 
formal classes, but the owner, Barbara Gregory, will "work with customers one 
on one" if they need assistance; it also has all necessary supplies. 
</P>
<P>
 Carrying supplies are The Doll &amp; Miniature Shoppe , and Miniature Estates, 
both in Los Angeles in Los Angeles; Casey's Wee Littles in Anaheim, and Tiny 
Town in Temple City. 
</P>
<P>
 Nutshell News magazine, published monthly by Kalmbach Publishing Co., 21027 
Crossroads Circle, P.O. Box 1612, Waukesha, Wis. 53187, includes how-to 
instructions and features many doll-house projects. 
</P>
<P>
 Dover Publications Inc. has issued several books specializing in doll houses: 
"Needlework Designs for Miniature Projects," by Eileen Folk; "Miniature Iron-On 
Transfer Patterns for Dollhouses, Dolls and Small Projects," by Rita Weiss and 
Frank Fontana; "Build Your Own Inexpensive Dollhouse," by E.J. Tangerman, and 
"Ready-to-Use Dollhouse Floor Coverings," "Ready-to-Use Victorian Dollhouse 
Wallpaper" and "Ready-to-Use Art Nouveau Dollhouse Wallpaper," all by Muncie 
Hendler. For a catalogue write, 31 E. 2nd St., Mineola, N.Y. 11501. 
</P>
</TEXT>
