<HEADLINE>
<P>
PINE STORAGE BIN KEEPS FRUIT, VEGETABLES FRESH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE ELLINGTON, Ellingson has been designing patterns and plans for the 
amateur woodworker since 1948. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Potatoes, onions and just about any other fruit or vegetables you keep on hand 
will stay fresh longer in this set of storage bins made of pine. 
</P>
<P>
The top shelf is flat, allowing you to store canned goods or dish towels, while 
the bottom two drawers are actual bins. The wire-mesh fronts of each bin allow 
the air to circulate around the foodstuff which, in turn, keeps moisture from 
rotting the fruits and vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
Measuring about 39 inches tall by 18 inches wide and 11 3/4 inches deep, this 
practical piece of furniture is easy enough for the amateur woodworker to 
complete. Our step-by-step directions, with accompanying photos, guide you in 
construction. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Cut All the Boards 
</P>
<P>
First, cut all the boards according to the schedule, and trace and cut the 
patterns for curves onto the appropriate boards. Assembly is a series of gluing 
and nailing the pieces together. The finishing hardware will be available to 
you locally, but we offer a source for ordering a complete package for your 
convenience. 
</P>
<P>
To obtain Storage Bins, Pattern No. 797, please send $4.50. Another kitchen 
convenience you might be looking for is our free-standing Chopping Block, 
Pattern No. 642, also $4.50, providing four square feet of work space and as 
easy to build as a box. 
</P>
<P>
Prices include postage and prompt handling. California residents add 6% sales 
tax. Send check or money order to Steve Ellington, c/o the Los Angeles Times, 
P.O. Box 2383, Van Nuys, Calif. 91409-2383. 
</P>
</TEXT>
