<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100889-0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 117783 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 8, 1989, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 99; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
734 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NIGHT MOVES: AT BEOGRAD, ROBUST FOOD, REVELRY TRANSLATE INTO ONE WORD: 
YUGOSLAVIAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENISE HAMILTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
You might not know Marshall Josip Tito from Archduke Francis Ferdinand. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps you've never entertained the notion of pljeskavica or raznjici. 
</P>
<P>
But consider, for a moment, Yugoslavia's robust wines, filo dough, stuffed meat 
pastries and Serbo-Croatian folk songs crooned by the Balkans' answer to Frank 
Sinatra. 
</P>
<P>
The proprietors of Beograd, a restaurant and nightclub in North Hollywood, have 
given all of these Yugoslavian amenities a great deal of consideration. The 
bland exterior of the restaurant, in a mini-mall near Magnolia and Cahuenga 
boulevards, gives little indication of the Slavic delights that lie within. 
</P>
<P>
The food is tasty, hearty and reasonably priced. The service is friendly 
without being overbearing. And where else in Los Angeles can you and your loved 
ones get serenaded by Zvomko Mitrovic, a pinstripe-suited Yugoslavian who puts 
his big Croatian heart into the songs he belts out to packed crowds each Friday 
and Saturday night? 
</P>
<P>
In the year since Ljijana Javorina and Vojkan Kalnic opened Beograd, the 
nondescript corner has turned into a little slice of Yugoslavia on weekend 
nights, attracting Americans as well as Montenegrans, Serbs, Croats and other 
representatives of Yugoslavia's six republics and two autonomous provinces who 
come to rekindle memories of their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
Don't be surprised if some of your fellow diners jump to their feet in the 
midst of their chicken Paprikash, link hands and begin dancing an ethnic 
fast-step that takes them in a half-circle around the room. 
</P>
<P>
Although Beograd opens at 5 p.m, things don't really kick into gear until about 
10:30 p.m. Sometimes the revelry extends late into the night. One recent Sunday 
morning at 1:30, the musicians were still singing to a packed (and rapt) house. 
</P>
<P>
Javorina and Kalnic used to own Yugoslavian Village, a now-closed restaurant on 
Barham Boulevard near Cahuenga. Kalnic, who often plays accordion in the house 
band, is in contact with musician friends he left behind in Belgrade 17 years 
ago. As a result, Beograd is a showcase for visiting Yugoslavian musicians, who 
come to Los Angeles for six-week stints. The revolving door ensures that 
singers know the newest Slavic pop songs in addition to more traditional fare. 
And there's no cover. 
</P>
<P>
One night, an accordion player from Belgrade coaxed unusual, vibrato-like 
sounds from his instrument, and Mitrovic's vocals evoked the quavering 
plaintive singing one associates with Islamic music. The band can switch to 
rousing polkas at the drop of a hat. Drum machines are verboten, and Mitrovic 
works the room like a celebrity entertainer in Las Vegas, maneuvering from 
table to table, trailing a long microphone cord, and trading jokes with the 
crowd in Serbo-Croatian. 
</P>
<P>
Since Yugoslavia was cobbled together after World War I from the republics of 
Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, Macedonia, Slovenia and Croatia and two 
autonomous provinces, Vojvodina and Kosovo, Yugoslavian cuisine, like its 
music, is really a melange of influences. But dieters be warned -- this is not 
low-cal food. 
</P>
<P>
Dinners run from $9.95 to $13.95 for specials and include a tomato-based spicy 
fish soup or salad that comes with "mysterious Yugoslavian dressing," according 
to a waitress. This translated into a salad of crisp romaine with what tasted 
like a Caesar dressing. 
</P>
<P>
Chicken breasts came stuffed with feta cheese, rolled in nutty-tasting bread 
crumbs and fried, accompanied by sauteed peppers, carrots, rice and potatoes. 
</P>
<P>
And the pljeskavica? That's a mixture of ground pork, beef, lamb and bell 
peppers served on a bed of onions. 
</P>
<P>
Among the desserts, palacsinka -- stuffed crepe suzettes topped with a 
chocolate sauce -- stands out. 
</P>
<P>
Beograd also offers strong, 12%-alcohol Yugoslavian beer for $3.50, mineral 
water, Turkish coffee and a variety of "Jugoslavian" wines at $11.95 a bottle. 
</P>
<P>
Javorina, who has worked in restaurants for 25 years and does most of the 
cooking, says she plans to get a Yugoslavian publishing house to start sending 
over some Belgrade newspapers to make her Slavic customers feel at home. 
</P>
<P>
But whether you're a Serb or an Angeleno, "When you come here, you feel like 
you are in Yugoslavia." 
</P>
<P>
Beograd, 10540 Magnolia Blvd., North Hollywood, is open from 5 to 10 p.m. 
Wednesday, Thursday and Sunday; from 5 p.m. until 2 a.m. Friday and Saturday. 
Visa and MasterCard accepted. (818) 766-8689. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
