</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Food and Drug Administration wants a New York pharmaceutical manufacturer 
to recall an antibiotic used to treat urinary tract infections because it 
believes the company cheated on product safety tests, an FDA official said. An 
FDA probe found indications that Bolar Pharmaceutical substituted the brand 
name product Macrodantin for its generic version of the drug nitrofurantoin in 
tests to win product approval, said FDA spokesman Jeff Nesbit. "Because of the 
evidence indicating a substitution, it is not possible for the FDA to assure 
whether the Bolar product is therapeutically equivalent to the brand name 
product at this time," Nesbit said. The Washington Post quoted Bolar President 
Robert Shulman as saying the company would decide by early this week whether to 
recall the product. Shulman said there is "no difference" between the drug that 
was tested and Bolar's version now on the market. 
