<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARMY BARS ISRAEL PEACE ACTIVISTS' WEST BANK CONVOY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIT LID, Israel 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The army set up a road block of jeeps and barbed wire Saturday to prevent a 
"peace convoy" of more than 1,000 Israelis from entering the West Bank town of 
Tulkarm to hold talks with Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
"This obstacle, this roadblock, it is symbolic, and there are many obstacles 
that the Israeli government tries to put up between the Israelis and the 
Palestinians," said Faisal Husseini, a prominent East Jerusalem Palestinian who 
was part of the convoy. 
</P>
<P>
The military had declared Tulkarm a closed military area and erected the 
roadblocks after Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin ordered the "Peace Day" visit 
to the West Bank town canceled. Peace activists said the military had no 
authority to stop the event because it was not planned as a demonstration but 
as a series of visits to Palestinian homes. 
</P>
<P>
Blocked from entering Tulkarm, the protesters filled the road at the western 
entrance to the town and unfurled banners reading "Peace Now." 
</P>
<P>
Left-wing Knesset members Haim Oron and Dedi Zucker criticized Israel's "Inner 
Cabinet" for rejecting Friday an Egyptian invitation to begin 
Israeli-Palestinian talks in Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ISRAEL -- ARMED FORCES; BLOCKADES; ISRAEL -- TERRITORIES AND POSSESSIONS; 
PALESTINIANS -- ISRAEL; WEST BANK (ISRAEL); PEACE MOVEMENTS; DEMONSTRATIONS -- 
ISRAEL; MIDDLE EAST PEACE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
