<HEADLINE>
<P>
BARRIER REMOVAL FOCUS OF MINE BLAST PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WHEATCROFT, Ky. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal mining investigator contends that a cinder block barrier was removed 
illegally from inside a coal mine about 15 minutes before an explosion that 
killed 10 people last month. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Finnie, a special investigator for the U.S. Mine Safety and Health 
Administration, said in a sworn statement submitted to a court Friday that 
removing the barrier disrupted air currents in the Pyro Mining Co. mine, 
creating dangerous levels of explosive methane. 
</P>
<P>
Ron Siler, president of Costain Coal Inc., parent to Pyro Mining, said last 
month that a barrier was taken down inside the Western Kentucky mine the 
morning of the explosion Sept. 13, but he said it was removed after the fatal 
blast, not 15 minutes before. 
</P>
<P>
He also contended that removal of the barrier could not have been a factor, 
even if it came before the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
