<HEADLINE>
<P>
EL CAMINO EASILY POWERS ITS WAY PAST GOLDEN WEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRENE GARCIA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There's little doubt after Saturday's Mission Conference win over Golden West 
College that El Camino College will dominate the rest of its opponents this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
The top-ranked Warriors (4-0, 3-0) seemed capable of anything in their 38-14 
victory over Golden West (2-2, 2-1), a team they tied last year. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino was so dominant that Coach John Featherstone put in his second-string 
quarterback and defense in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Why not? with 14:50 left to play, the Warriors already had a 31-point lead. 
Might as well give sophomore quarterback Frank Dolce a rest. He had already 
completed 22 of 28 yards for 300 yards and 4 touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
With 8:20 left in the third quarter, El Camino scored on a five-play, 93-yard 
drive. Running back Alfred Lowe scored on a two-yard touchdown run and Dolce 
threw to Khevin Pratt for the two-point conversion to give the Warriors a 31-7 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino scored on its last touchdown early in the fourth quarter when Dolce 
passed to David Blakes for a 29-yard pass. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West scored on its second touchdown with less than a minute left to play 
when third-string quarterback Ron Ramirez hit Robert Bedford for a nine-yard 
pass. 
</P>
<P>
"I thought our running game is what kept them off balance," Featherstone said. 
"We ran so we could get our big plays through the air." 
</P>
<P>
The Warriors were on a roll from the start. They scored on their first 
possession, which came after Anthony Anetema intercepted a Rip Flippo pass down 
the middle. Golden West drove 30 yards in four plays before turning the ball 
over to the Warriors. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino capped a five-play, 61-yard drive with a 16-yard screen pass from 
Dolce to Al Savea for the first score of the game. Louis Perez' point-after 
kick put the Warriors up 7-0. 
</P>
<P>
Perez made a 27-yard field goal on the Warriors' next possession to make it 
10-0. The Warriors got the ball when Ed Togia recovered Corey Dickson's fumble 
during a punt return. 
</P>
<P>
The Warriors marched 32 yards, including a three-yard touchdown run by Dolce 
that was called back on a holding penalty. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino scored a touchdown on its next possession, though. The Warriors drove 
52 yards in eight plays and Perez' point-after kick made it 17-0. Dolce threw a 
16-yard touchdown pass to Shannon Thompson for that score. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West finally scored with 11:20 left in the half, thanks to an El Camino 
fumble by Alfred Lowe on the Golden West 15-yard line. 
</P>
<P>
Rustler defensive lineman Robert Erena recovered the ball and Flippo hit Patric 
Reilly for a 15-yard touchdown pass on third-and-ten. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino answered with another touchdown. It came after a nine-play, 78-yard 
drive that was capped by Dolce's 25-yard pass to David Blakes. That gave the 
Warriors a comfortable 23-7 halftime lead. 
</P>
<P>
The Warriors take their Mission Conference show to Chula Vista next week where 
they face unranked Southwestern, a 28-0 loser to Rancho Santiago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
